The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, August 26, 2004 				 Stage set for bills to boost banks, bourses
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Aug. 25: The Union cabinet today approved amendments to important legislations in order to streamline and strengthen banking and stock market operations.																								The cabinet meeting, chaired by Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, cleared the amendments to the Banking Regulation Act 1949, Securities Contract Regulation Act 1956 and the Depositories Act 1996, an official spokesperson said. The United Progressive Alliance (UPA) government will introduce two bills in Parliament either in this session or the next to give effect to these amendments.																								The cabinet also approved a proposal to open talks with the Nepal government so that designated bus operators of Bihar, West Bengal, Uttar Pradesh, Uttaranchal and Delhi can finalise the draft agreement and protocol with their Nepalese counterparts.																								They will also have to involve the representatives from ministries of external affairs, home affairs, defence, department of commerce and revenue (customs) in this regard.																								The cabinet gave an ex post facto approval for the acceptance of inter-governmental agreement on Asian Highways. This agreement was signed during the 60th session of the United National Economic and Social Commission for Asia Pacific (UNESCAP) held in April at Shanghai.																								This will help the movement of traffic, trade and boost tourism across Asian countries. At present, this highway network extends to 32 countries covering 14,000 kilometres.																								The cabinet also approved the extension of the term of the National Commission for Safai Karamcharis till December 31, 2007. However, the commissions strength has been reduced to five from seven. It will now have one chairperson and four members, including one woman. 																								The chairperson of the commission will hold the rank of a minister of state while the four members will have the status of secretaries to the government. The commission evaluates the implementation of programme and schemes relating to social and economic development of safai karmacharis and makes recommendations to the government.																								The cabinet gave another ex post facto approval for signing and ratification of the agreement on Juridical and Judicial Cooperation in civil and commercial matters with Bahrain.																								Meanwhile, the cabinet committee on economic affairs (CCEA) today approved an outlay of Rs 568.17 crore, including a central share of Rs 472.60 crore, to implement the technology mission on cotton (TMC) during the Tenth Plan. The implementation of TMC is expected to increase the cotton production to about 215 lakh bales by the end of the Tenth plan.																								The productivity level is also expected to increase to 388 kg per hectare from the current level of 269 kg per hectare.																								The CCEA also approved a proposal to award a contract to Dubai Ports International of the UAE for the development and operation of international container trans-shipment terminal in Cochin port through private sector participation on build-operate-and-transfer basis for a period of 30 years. 
